re, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Watling Street, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1470–":"about 1470–Deceased","1485–1524":"1485–1524","1520–1591":"1520–1591","1522–Male":"1522–Deceased","1470–Female":"1470–Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1470":"about 1470","1524":"1524","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","1485":"1485","about 1522":"about 1522","1571":"1571","1470":"1470","1591":"1591","1549":"1549","England":"England","Wroxeter, Shropshire, England,":"Wroxeter, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Watling Street, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Charlton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): habitational name from North Charlton or Charlton near Bellingham (both Northumberland) or from any of the many other places so named (there are over ninety examples in England), from Old English <i>Ceorlatūn</i> ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) of the peasants’. Old English <i>ceorl</i> denoted originally a free peasant of the lowest rank, later (but probably already before the Norman conquest) a tenant in pure villeinage, a serf or bondsman.","Irish: altered form of   Carlin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carlton","meanings":["English (northern and eastern England): habitational name from any of various places called Carlton (Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Durham, Lincolnshire, Leicestershire, Nottinghamshire, Northamptonshire, Suffolk, East Yorkshire, Yorkshire, and North Yorkshire) or Carleton (Cumberland, Lancashire, Norfolk, Yorkshire). All come from Old Norse <i>karl</i> ‘common man, peasant’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’ (compare   Charlton  ). Places spelled <i>Carl(e)ton</i> (as opposed to <i>Charlton</i>) are in areas of Scandinavian settlement, mostly in northern England.","Irish (Antrim): variant of   Carleton   2."]},{"name":"Carlin","meanings":["Irish (North Ulster; now also common in Scotland): from <b>Ó Cearbhalláin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cearbhallán</i>’, a diminutive of the personal name <i>Cearbhall</i> (see   Carroll  ).","English: variant of   Carling  .","Italian (Veneto): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Carlo</i>, Italian form of   Charles  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":79,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":88,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":99,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":101,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Charlton was born about 1470, in England. She married John Forester, The Younger. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1470–":"umbes 1470–Surnud","1485–1524":"1485–1524","1520–1591":"1520–1591","1522–Male":"1522–Surnud","1470–Female":"1470–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1470":"umbes 1470","1524":"1524","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","1485":"1485","about 1522":"umbes 1522","1571":"1571","1470":"1470","1591":"1591","1549":"1549","England":"England","Wroxeter, Shropshire, England,":"Wroxeter, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Watling Street, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1470–":"noin 1470–Kuollut","1485–1524":"1485–1524","1520–1591":"1520–1591","1522–Male":"1522–Kuollut","1470–Female":"1470–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1470":"noin 1470","1524":"1524","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","1485":"1485","about 1522":"noin 1522","1571":"1571","1470":"1470","1591":"1591","1549":"1549","England":"England","Wroxeter, Shropshire, England,":"Wroxeter, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Watling Street, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1470–":"environ 1470–Décédée","1485–1524":"1485–1524","1520–1591":"1520–1591","1522–Male":"1522–Décédé","1470–Female":"1470–Décédée","1569":"1569","1558":"1558